  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Every seller says they are going to declutter before listing. Most do not really understand what that means in practice until the skip bin is in the driveway and they are halfway through the garage at 11am on a Saturday. The clear-out before a sale is not the same as an ordinary tidy up. It is an industrial-scale removal of stuff that the house has accumulated over five, ten, or twenty years of normal life. Treating it as the logistical exercise it actually is will save you weekends of effort and produce a better-presenting home at the end.</p>

      <p>This article is the practical partner to our piece on decluttering and depersonalising. That one covers why and what. This one covers how: what size skip bin to hire, what rules apply in Brisbane, how to sort efficiently, and where things go that cannot go in the bin.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Start with a realistic estimate of volume</h2>
      <p>The biggest single mistake is under-sizing the skip. Sellers typically hire a 3 cubic metre bin, fill it in the first weekend, and then need a second or third bin to finish the job. Two or three smaller bins usually cost more than one large bin hired once. For a full family home clear-out before listing in Bulimba, Hawthorne, Morningside, or any of the surrounding inner-east suburbs, a 6 or 8 cubic metre skip is the realistic starting size. For larger Queenslanders with deep underneath storage, a garage full of legacy items, or a shed that has not been emptied in a decade, a 9 or 12 cubic metre bin is often what the job actually requires.</p>

      <p>A useful way to think about volume: a 6 cubic metre skip is roughly the size of six standard wheelie bins lined up and six deep, or about two car loads to a council tip. Most families have more than two car loads of material to clear once they start looking properly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Brisbane skip bin logistics</h2>
      <p>Skip bin providers across Brisbane inner east will deliver on short notice, typically within 24 to 48 hours. Hire periods are usually three to seven days, with extensions available for a daily fee. Expect to pay roughly $400 to $700 for a 6 cubic metre general waste bin, and $600 to $900 for a 9 cubic metre. Prices vary depending on waste type, suburb, and how quickly you need the bin delivered.</p>

      <p>Bin placement matters. A skip on your property (driveway, front lawn) needs no permit. A skip placed on the kerb or nature strip in a Brisbane City Council area requires a permit from council, which the skip provider should arrange on your behalf. Do not place a skip on the street without a permit: fines apply and you may also be liable for any damage to the footpath or road surface. If your driveway is sloped, confirm with the provider that their truck can safely load and unload on the gradient.</p>

      <p>Most providers separate waste into general waste (mixed), heavy waste (concrete, tiles, bricks), and green waste (garden material). Mixing the wrong material into the wrong bin can result in the whole load being charged at a higher tip rate or rejected at the transfer station, with a callback fee. Ask the provider what is and is not allowed before you start loading.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What cannot go in a general skip</h2>
      <p>Several categories of material are either prohibited or surcharged in a standard general waste skip. These need a separate plan:</p>
      <p>Paints, solvents, and pool chemicals are hazardous waste. Brisbane City Council runs free residential chemical drop-off days several times a year. Store these items separately and book a drop-off day rather than putting them in the skip.</p>
      <p>Batteries (car, household, power tool) are banned from general waste. Most major hardware stores and council transfer stations accept them for free recycling.</p>
      <p>Whitegoods containing refrigerant (fridges, freezers, air conditioners) usually attract a degassing fee either in the skip or at the tip. Some retailers will take an old fridge when they deliver a new one, which is the cheapest option if timing aligns.</p>
      <p>Tyres cost extra in a skip and can often be disposed of more cheaply at a local tyre dealer, sometimes free when you replace them.</p>
      <p>Asbestos must not go in a general skip under any circumstances. If you suspect any material in your home contains asbestos (fibro sheeting, old vinyl floor tiles, some roof materials, some eaves), stop and engage a licensed asbestos removalist. This is a legal and health-critical point.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The sorting method that actually works</h2>
      <p>The most efficient clear-out method is not to start at the front door and work backward. It is to work room by room, with a single pass per room, making only four decisions per item: keep, sell, donate, or skip. Second-guessing is the enemy. The clear-out takes twice as long when each item becomes a conversation.</p>

      <p>Keep means it is going with you to the next home. Pack it into labelled boxes as you go, and move those boxes to a single staging area (usually the garage).</p>
      <p>Sell means Facebook Marketplace, Gumtree, or a garage sale. Be realistic: if an item will not genuinely sell inside two weeks, put it in donate or skip. Time is the variable people underestimate.</p>
      <p>Donate means St Vincent de Paul, Lifeline, the Salvation Army, or a local specific charity. Most will collect larger items (furniture, appliances in working order) for free with notice. They will not collect damaged, stained, or broken goods, so be honest about condition before you call.</p>
      <p>Skip means it goes in the bin. Torn, broken, stained, or obsolete items are skip items. Do not waste effort trying to rehome items that will not be used.</p>

      <p>Many sellers find it easier to work with a single trusted friend or family member rather than alone. Another person forces the four-decision discipline: you cannot drift into a two-hour reminiscence about every item if someone else is waiting for your answer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Priority areas in a Brisbane home</h2>
      <p>Some areas produce more visible improvement per hour of work than others. Focus there first.</p>

      <p>The garage is usually the single biggest volume source. It is also the first space most buyers see when they walk around the side. A cleared garage with a visible floor and wall space communicates order to a buyer more powerfully than almost any other room.</p>

      <p>Underneath storage (the space under a raised Queenslander) is the second biggest volume source and one of the hardest spaces to enter at an open home. Buyers will look. Clearing it properly reveals usable square metreage that dramatically affects buyer perception of the home.</p>

      <p>Kitchen cupboards, pantries, and bathroom vanities come next. Buyers open these. Overflowing cupboards signal insufficient storage even when the house has plenty.</p>

      <p>Bedrooms, especially wardrobes, are fourth. A half-empty wardrobe looks like space. A full one looks like a problem. Most sellers need to pack and remove at least a third of the clothing in a family wardrobe before styling photography.</p>

      <p>Outdoor sheds, planters, and yard clutter matter a lot in Brisbane. A tidy outdoor area is worth significant money in a market where outdoor living is central to the buyer appeal of inner-east homes.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Budget and time estimates</h2>
      <p>For a typical inner-east family home (three to four bedrooms, garage, backyard, possibly underneath storage), allow the following:</p>
      <p>A 6 cubic metre skip: $400 to $700, for a 3 to 7 day hire.</p>
      <p>Professional removalists for larger items or post-sort clearing: $500 to $1,500 depending on scope.</p>
      <p>Tip fees for items outside the skip (tyres, whitegoods, special waste): $100 to $300.</p>
      <p>Time: realistically 20 to 40 hours of active work, spread over two to three weekends and a few weeknights. Sellers who plan for this rather than trying to fit it around ordinary life complete it faster and with less family stress.</p>

      <p>If the property is tenanted, being estate-cleared, or the seller has limited physical capacity, a full-service decluttering or clearance provider can be hired to do the whole job. Expect $3,000 to $7,000 for a full home clearance in Brisbane, depending on volume. For some sellers, particularly executors of a deceased estate, this is money well spent and unlocks the sale campaign faster than trying to do it personally.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Finishing touches that signal a cared-for home</h2>
      <p>Once the bulk clear-out is done, a few small additions make a disproportionate difference. A clean driveway with no oil stains, pressure-washed front pavers, trimmed edges on the lawn, and empty bins on the inspection days. The goal is for a buyer to arrive and see a home that is ready, not a home mid-project. Buyers read signals. A visible clear-out signals that the seller is serious, organised, and has cared for the home. That signal carries into the price they are willing to pay.</p>

